# Backend Recompile — Force Clean Compile After Java Changes

**Problem:** Maven's incremental compiler (`maven-compiler-plugin`) caches compiled classes in `target/classes/`. When Java source files are modified (especially enums, new classes, or renamed fields), the compiler can decide "Nothing to compile - all classes are up to date" and **skip compilation entirely**. The backend then runs with **stale bytecode** that does not include the changes. This causes silent bugs (e.g. new enum values fall through to defaults, new classes are not found, changed logic is not applied).

**How we've been bitten:** Adding `RENDER_EMAIL_TEMPLATE` to the `StepType` enum in `WorkflowDefinition.java` — the backend kept using the old bytecode without the new enum value, so `fromString("RENDER_EMAIL_TEMPLATE")` silently fell back to `TASK`. The step looked correct on drag-and-drop (frontend-only) but reverted to a generic TASK on save/reload (backend used old enum).

**Rule:** After modifying **any** Java source file under `workflow-engine/src/main/java/`, you **must** run a forced clean compile before restarting the backend.

## Mandatory steps

### 1. Force clean compile

```bash
cd workflow/micro-services/workflow-engine
mvn clean compile -DskipTests -q
```

This deletes `target/` and recompiles all sources from scratch.

### 2. Verify critical changes (when adding enums, classes, or fields)

For **enum changes** (e.g. new `StepType` value), verify the compiled bytecode includes the change:

```bash
javap -p target/classes/com/liliflow/workflow/provider/model/WorkflowDefinition\$StepType.class | grep -i "MY_NEW_ENUM"
```

For **new classes**, verify the `.class` file exists:

```bash
ls target/classes/com/liliflow/workflow/path/to/MyNewClass.class
```

### 3. Restart the backend

After clean compile, restart the workflow engine:

- If using `restart.sh`: it runs `mvn spring-boot:run` which will see the freshly compiled classes as up-to-date (good — no double compile).
- If restarting manually: `mvn spring-boot:run` from the workflow-engine directory.

### 4. Confirm in startup log

Check the first lines of `backend.log`. You should **not** see:

```
[INFO] Nothing to compile - all classes are up to date
```

If you see that line after a `mvn clean compile`, something went wrong (Maven is looking at a different `target/`). Verify your working directory.

## When this applies

- You add or remove an **enum constant** (e.g. `StepType`, `WorkflowDefinitionState`)
- You add a **new Java class** (e.g. new executor, service, entity)
- You change **method signatures**, **field types**, or **annotations** (e.g. `@JsonCreator`, `@Column`)
- You modify **any** `.java` file and plan to test it against the running backend
- You are debugging a "works in frontend but not in backend" issue

## Common symptoms of stale bytecode

| Symptom | Likely cause |
|---------|-------------|
| New enum value silently falls back to default (e.g. TASK) | Enum constant not in compiled bytecode |
| `ClassNotFoundException` or `NoSuchMethodError` at runtime | New/renamed class or method not compiled |
| Backend ignores code changes you just made | `target/classes/` has old `.class` files |
| `backend.log` shows "Nothing to compile" after source changes | Maven's incremental compiler didn't detect the change |

